About this item

  • 3-Way WiFi Switch Dimmer: Both Master & Add-on Switches are dimmable. Support INC bulb (400W), Dimmable LED (150W) and CFL bulb (150W). The add-on switch CAN NOT work independently. It must work with our master switch. The master switch CAN NOT work with other standard 3 way switches
  • Home Automation System: Compatible with Alexa and Google Home Voice Control (Smart Life Skill), Remote Control via Smart Life App on iOS and Android. No Hub is required for Wi-Fi Dimmer Switch
  • Installation: Follow the user manual on website. Live and neutral wires are required for the master switch, 2.4G Wi-Fi ONLY (Not 5G Wi-Fi), Adjust the lowest brightness on the Master switch. This is 3-way kit (two switches control same lights), For 4-way, please puchase one more add-on switch in our store.
  • Advantage: Lowest brightness calibration, Over Temperature Protection, Wiring Error Alarm & Protection, Brightness Memory, Soft On & Soft Off Lighting for Comfortable Visual Effect, Responsiveness Physical Button
  • Warranty: we offer 90-Day 100% refund, 1-year Quality Warranty. Promptly tech support online. Send us wiring photos if it cannot work after installation

Safety Information

Product Description

This is the first WiFi 3-way smart dimmer switch on Amazon. We released it in early 2019, and it works well in thousands of houses now. This 3-way kit has following features:

  1. Dimmer at both master and secondary locations;
  2. Calibration Knob to reduce flickering;
  3. Expand-ability to work for 4-way and more.

FREE iOS and Android App

This 3-way set can let you dim from both master and add-on sides. It's better than traditional dimmer, which can only dim at one side.

Voice Activated Smart Home

It is compatible with Alexa and Google Assistant for voice control. This is the most important part of home automation system.

Start Dimming

This switch can work with most of the dimmable LED lights to offer you a good dimming experience like traditional dimmer.

App Control

SmartLife App is a popular home automation app in the US. It is FREE in App Store, Google Play and Alexa Skills.

Rated Voltage 100-120VAC
Max Power LED (150W max), INC (400W max)
Dimmer Dimmable from both master and add-on sides
Wi-Fi 2.4GHz Only, NOT 5G
Installation Master switch needs neutral wires and hot live wire

How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

  • Kyle :D
    5.0 out of 5 stars 3 Way Smart Switch Dimmer is FANTASTIC!
    Reviewed in the United States on February 10, 2019
    Verified Purchase
    Currently, I have 15 dimmer and 18 regular Martin Jerry switches installed in my house. I can't say enough good things about their performance and price.

    On February 1, the single dimmer switch product page showed a second option available, the long-awaited 3 way dimmer switch package.

    The 3 way dimmer switch was $51 on Lightning Deal. They weren't available for immediate shipping due to the initial release date, but I purchased two with no worry. I received and installed them just 5 days later.

    Cons:

    Not actually cons, just things I think would make an already awesome product just about perfect.

    1. In my opinion, $51 on Lightning Deal is not as good a deal as their other products on LD. But compared to every other option out there for a 3 way smart switch, it's a great price. I'm just happy I only need two of these setups. Collectively, that's $102 to control two lights with four switches. Maybe I'm just spoiled by the affordability of their other switches.

    2. The LEDs that show the brightness level do not light up on the secondary switch. Only the primary switch has those light up alongside the rocker. It's not a deal breaker, but I don't know the reason for that limitation. It's a "would be nice to have" thing.

    Pros:

    1. It's a 3 way smart switch setup for $51 (on LD)!!!

    2. For installation instructions, I scanned a QR code on the caution sticker they use to tape the wires down. I had some initial confusion on exactly how things hooked up, BUT THEN I READ THE INSTRUCTIONS ALL THE WAY THROUGH. The instructions and diagram are clear on what goes where. Just read them through before starting. It's an easy install.

    3. The primary switch has THREE awesome new features pertaining to the dimmer function (compared to the regular dimmer switches). The first two are what the LED lights do when the light is off. The first is that a single dim LED remains lit to show you what level the brightness will be when you turn the light back on. This is nice. The second is that the level can be adjusted while the light is off, and the single dim LED moves accordingly. This is awesome.

    4. The third awesome new feature is the dimmer calibration! There's a dial under the body of the primary switch. Use the rocker to dim the switch all the way down. Then use the dial to calibrate that even further to get the light as dim as possible. This does not affect full brightness at all. The only bad thing about this is that I wish all 15 of my regular dimmer switches had the dial (and the other two new features)! It makes a big difference in how low you can dim your light.

    Two quick tips.

    1. Before you install, go buy a handful of wire nuts that are 2-3 sizes bigger than those provided with the switches. They are fine with 2 and 3 wires, like you see in a single gang box, but I've run into issues when I've installed in a multiple gang box, where neutrals and grounds were already 3 or more wires together. The provided wire nuts are not large enough to handle adding another 1 or 2 wires in these instances.

    2. How dim your light will go depends on what type of bulb you use. If you replace the bulb with a different type, just pop the cover off, unscrew the bottom of the switch enough so you can pull it out and access the dial, then calibrate.

    It's obvious that I like and trust Martin Jerry's products, and this new 3 way switch does not disappoint at all. I'm extremely satisfied, and I'm excited to see what else they come out with in the future.

    5.0 out of 5 stars 3-Way Wifi Dimmer is Awesome
    Reviewed in the United States on May 8, 2019
    Verified Purchase
    I recently installed Google Home, and have been progressively installing Martin Jerry WiFi switches, and I love these switches. They are easy to install, they fit nicely in the J-boxes, they look nice once the switch plate goes on, they connect quickly and easily to the home's Wifi via Martin Jerry's SmartLife app -- and, as an added bonus, the app even remembers all the details of your WiFi setup, and pre-fills everything in (including the password) when go to set up another switch. And if the WiFi signal at the switch is weak, the app offers two 'fallback' methods of connecting the switch (the first one, "default installation," worked for me on the first try). The only way they could make this any easier would be if they came to my home and installed the things for me.

    So far, I've installed SPST ("single pole") switches, dimmer switches, 3-way dinner switches, and 4-way dimmer switches -- more than two dozen switches so far (and counting). All work great. I recently installed LED bulbs throughout the home (we just purchased it); the LED bulbs were flickering with the old Lutron dimmer switches -- but once I installed the Martin Jerrys, NO MORE FLICKER!

    I'd give these switches 6 stars if I could.

    One request for Martin Jerry, if they're paying attention: A 3-way SPST switch would really help "round out" your line. And a single-gang DPST switch would be nice, too (two switches in a single stack; to keep it easy, just have a single hot and a single neutral, with each switch controlling one load -- and the ability in the app to control the two switches independently.
